steps.description:
Connect to the running fork at ws://localhost:8000.

```typescript
Via Polkadot.js API (TypeScript):
  import { ApiPromise, WsProvider } from '@polkadot/api';
  const api = await ApiPromise.create({ provider: new WsProvider('ws://localhost:8000') });
  const block = await api.rpc.chain.getBlock();
  console.log('Fork head:', block.block.header.number.toNumber());
```

Via Polkadot.js Apps UI: navigate to polkadot.js.org/apps, select network > Development > Custom, enter ws://localhost:8000, and click Switch.

To manipulate storage via the dev_setStorage WebSocket command (using wscat or a JS client):
  { "jsonrpc": "2.0", "id": 1, "method": "dev_setStorage", "params": [{ "System": { "Account": [["0xALICE_KEY", { "data": { "free": 1000000000000 } }]] } }] }

Create a test file in the tests directory (e.g., ./tests/balance.test.ts). Moonwall uses the describeSuite function to define test suites:

```typescript
  import { describeSuite, expect } from '@moonwall/cli';

  describeSuite({
    id: 'D01',
    title: 'Balance transfer test',
    foundationMethods: 'dev',
    testCases: ({ it, context }) => {
      it('C100', 'Alice should have a balance', async () => {
        const api = context.polkadotJs();
        const accounts = await api.query.system.account('5GrwvaEF5zXb26Fz9rcQpDWS57CtERHpNehXCPcNoHGKutQY');
        expect(accounts.data.free.toBigInt()).toBeGreaterThan(0n);
      });
    },
  });
```

Each test case requires a unique ID ('C100'), a title, and an async function receiving it (test runner) and context (provides the polkadotJs API). The API is initialized by Moonwall before tests run — do not create API connections manually.

Create the empty tests.rs file. Then open src/lib.rs and add the following two lines immediately after the mock module declaration:

```rust
#[cfg(test)]
mod tests;
```

The module declarations in lib.rs should now read:
#[cfg(test)] mod mock;
#[cfg(test)] mod tests;

Open src/tests.rs and write these imports at the top:

```rust
use crate::{mock::*, Error, Event};
use frame::deps::frame_support::{assert_noop, assert_ok};
use frame::deps::sp_runtime::DispatchError;
```

These bring in: all mock runtime items (Test, new_test_ext*, RuntimeOrigin, System, CustomPallet, CounterValue, UserInteractions), the pallet Error and Event enums, FRAME assertion macros, and DispatchError for origin checks.

Create pallets/pallet-custom/src/benchmarking.rs with:

```rust
#![cfg(feature = "runtime-benchmarks")]
use super::*;
use frame::deps::frame_benchmarking::v2::*;
use frame::benchmarking::prelude::RawOrigin;

#[benchmarks]
mod benchmarks {
    use super::*;

    #[benchmark]
    fn set_counter_value() {
        let new_value: u32 = 100;
        #[extrinsic_call]
        _(RawOrigin::Root, new_value);
        assert_eq!(CounterValue::<T>::get(), new_value);
    }

    #[benchmark]
    fn increment() {
        let caller: T::AccountId = whitelisted_caller();
        let amount: u32 = 50;
        #[extrinsic_call]
        _(RawOrigin::Signed(caller.clone()), amount);
        assert_eq!(CounterValue::<T>::get(), amount);
        assert_eq!(UserInteractions::<T>::get(caller), 1);
    }

    #[benchmark]
    fn decrement() {
        CounterValue::<T>::put(100);
        let caller: T::AccountId = whitelisted_caller();
        let amount: u32 = 30;
        #[extrinsic_call]
        _(RawOrigin::Signed(caller.clone()), amount);
        assert_eq!(CounterValue::<T>::get(), 70);
    }
```

    impl_benchmark_test_suite!(Pallet, crate::mock::new_test_ext(), crate::mock::Test);
}

For a different pallet, update function names and assertions accordingly.

Create pallets/pallet-custom/src/weights.rs with a WeightInfo trait and () placeholder implementation:

```rust
pub trait WeightInfo {
    fn set_counter_value() -> frame::prelude::Weight;
    fn increment() -> frame::prelude::Weight;
    fn decrement() -> frame::prelude::Weight;
}

impl WeightInfo for () {
    fn set_counter_value() -> frame::prelude::Weight { frame::prelude::Weight::from_parts(10_000, 0) }
    fn increment() -> frame::prelude::Weight { frame::prelude::Weight::from_parts(15_000, 0) }
    fn decrement() -> frame::prelude::Weight { frame::prelude::Weight::from_parts(15_000, 0) }
}
```

The () impl is used in tests; benchmark-generated values will replace this file in the final step.

After running benchmarks, weights.rs is generated with measured weights. Follow these steps to integrate them:

1. The generated weights.rs includes a SubstrateWeight struct. The file structure looks like:

```rust
pub trait WeightInfo {
    fn set_counter_value() -> Weight;
    fn increment() -> Weight;
    fn decrement() -> Weight;
}

pub struct SubstrateWeight<T>(PhantomData<T>);
impl<T: frame_system::Config> WeightInfo for SubstrateWeight<T> {
    fn set_counter_value() -> Weight {
        Weight::from_parts(8_234_000, 0)
            .saturating_add(T::DbWeight::get().reads(1))
            .saturating_add(T::DbWeight::get().writes(1))
    }
    // ... increment and decrement similarly
}
```

2. Update runtime/src/configs/mod.rs to use the measured weights instead of the () placeholder:

```rust
impl pallet_custom::Config for Runtime {
    type RuntimeEvent = RuntimeEvent;
    type CounterMaxValue = ConstU32<1000>;
    type WeightInfo = pallet_custom::weights::SubstrateWeight<Runtime>;
}
```

The actual weight values will vary based on your hardware. The DbWeight accounts for database read/write operations. Now users' transactions will be charged using accurate measured weights.

Open `main.ts` and append the following block immediately before the end of `main()` (or wherever the connection is established) so the script queries account balance and cleanly disconnects:

```typescript
const balance = await client.query.system.account('INSERT_ADDRESS');
console.log('Free balance:', balance.data.free);
await client.disconnect();
```

Replace `INSERT_ADDRESS` with the same SS58 address you used in the previous step.

Fetch the reference file `watch-on-chain-events.ts` and save it as `watch-events.ts`. The file demonstrates the event-watching pattern using `client.events.system.NewAccount.watch()`:

```typescript
const unsub = await client.events.system.NewAccount.watch((events) => {
  console.log('New Account Created', events);
});
```

Integrate this in `main.ts` by adding it after the client connects and before `client.disconnect()`. Replace `system.NewAccount` with any `<pallet>.<EventName>` to watch a different event. Call `unsub()` to unsubscribe when done.

Create the expected directory structure (contracts/, scripts/, abis/, artifacts/), then fetch the reference file `Storage.sol` and save it as `contracts/Storage.sol`. The contract has a `storedNumber` public state variable and a `setNumber(uint256 _newNumber)` setter:

```solidity
// SPDX-License-Identifier: GPL-3.0
pragma solidity ^0.8.9;

contract Storage {
    uint256 public storedNumber;
    function setNumber(uint256 _newNumber) public { storedNumber = _newNumber; }
}
```

Open runtime/src/configs/mod.rs. Add the Config implementation for pallet-utility at the end of the file:

```rust
impl pallet_utility::Config for Runtime {
    type RuntimeEvent = RuntimeEvent;
    type RuntimeCall = RuntimeCall;
    type PalletsOrigin = OriginCaller;
    type WeightInfo = pallet_utility::weights::SubstrateWeight<Runtime>;
}
```

Place this impl block at the end of the file, after other pallet Config impls. All required associated types must be specified — the Rust compiler will list missing types if any are omitted.

Open runtime/src/configs/mod.rs. Add the first instance's Config implementation. The pallet-collective Config now includes additional fields for proposal management and governance control:

```rust
/// Configure the Technical Committee collective
impl pallet_collective::Config<Instance1> for Runtime {
    type RuntimeOrigin = RuntimeOrigin;
    type Proposal = RuntimeCall;
    type RuntimeEvent = RuntimeEvent;
    type MotionDuration = ConstU32<5>;
    type MaxProposals = ConstU32<100>;
    type MaxMembers = ConstU32<100>;
    type DefaultVote = pallet_collective::MoreThanMajorityThenPrimeDefaultVote;
    type SetMembersOrigin = EnsureRoot<AccountId>;
    type WeightInfo = pallet_collective::weights::SubstrateWeight<Runtime>;
    type MaxProposalWeight = ConstU64<{ u64::MAX / 2 }>;
    type DisapproveOrigin = EnsureRoot<Self::AccountId>;
    type KillOrigin = EnsureRoot<Self::AccountId>;
    type Consideration = ();
}
```

Key fields: DefaultVote uses MoreThanMajorityThenPrimeDefaultVote (majority with prime member tiebreaker); MaxProposalWeight caps proposal computational weight; DisapproveOrigin and KillOrigin control who can reject/kill proposals.

Add the second instance's Config immediately after the first in runtime/src/configs/mod.rs:

```rust
/// Configure the Council collective
impl pallet_collective::Config<Instance2> for Runtime {
    type RuntimeOrigin = RuntimeOrigin;
    type Proposal = RuntimeCall;
    type RuntimeEvent = RuntimeEvent;
    type MotionDuration = ConstU32<7>;
    type MaxProposals = ConstU32<50>;
    type MaxMembers = ConstU32<20>;
    type DefaultVote = pallet_collective::MoreThanMajorityThenPrimeDefaultVote;
    type SetMembersOrigin = EnsureRoot<AccountId>;
    type WeightInfo = pallet_collective::weights::SubstrateWeight<Runtime>;
    type MaxProposalWeight = ConstU64<{ u64::MAX / 2 }>;
    type DisapproveOrigin = EnsureRoot<Self::AccountId>;
    type KillOrigin = EnsureRoot<Self::AccountId>;
    type Consideration = ();
}
```

Both instances share the same pallet code but maintain completely independent storage. MotionDuration, MaxProposals, and MaxMembers can differ per instance.

Find the #[frame_support::runtime] macro block in runtime/src/lib.rs and add both instances with unique pallet_index values:

```rust
#[frame_support::runtime]
mod runtime {
    // ... existing pallets ...

    #[runtime::pallet_index(50)]
    pub type TechnicalCommittee = pallet_collective<Instance1>;

    #[runtime::pallet_index(51)]
    pub type Council = pallet_collective<Instance2>;
}
```

Choose pallet_index values (e.g., 50 and 51) not used by any other pallet. The names TechnicalCommittee and Council become the on-chain pallet identifiers for storage and extrinsics — choose carefully as renaming requires a migration.

Open pallets/pallet-custom/src/lib.rs and delete all existing content. Implement the counter pallet using the unified `frame` import:

```rust
#![cfg_attr(not(feature = "std"), no_std)]

extern crate alloc;

pub use pallet::*;

#[frame::pallet]
pub mod pallet {
    use alloc::vec::Vec;
    use frame::prelude::*;

    #[pallet::pallet]
    pub struct Pallet<T>(_);

    #[pallet::config]
    pub trait Config: frame_system::Config {
        type RuntimeEvent: From<Event<Self>> + IsType<<Self as frame_system::Config>::RuntimeEvent>;

        #[pallet::constant]
        type CounterMaxValue: Get<u32>;
    }

    #[pallet::event]
    #[pallet::generate_deposit(pub(super) fn deposit_event)]
    pub enum Event<T: Config> {
        CounterIncremented { new_value: u32, who: T::AccountId },
        CounterDecremented { new_value: u32, who: T::AccountId },
    }

    #[pallet::error]
    pub enum Error<T> {
        Overflow,
        Underflow,
        CounterMaxValueExceeded,
    }

    #[pallet::storage]
    pub type CounterValue<T> = StorageValue<_, u32, ValueQuery>;

    #[pallet::call]
    impl<T: Config> Pallet<T> {
        #[pallet::call_index(0)]
        #[pallet::weight(10_000)]
        pub fn increment(origin: OriginFor<T>) -> DispatchResult {
            let who = ensure_signed(origin)?;
            CounterValue::<T>::try_mutate(|val| {
                let new_val = val.checked_add(1).ok_or(Error::<T>::Overflow)?;
                ensure!(new_val <= T::CounterMaxValue::get(), Error::<T>::CounterMaxValueExceeded);
                *val = new_val;
                Self::deposit_event(Event::CounterIncremented { new_value: new_val, who });
                Ok(())
            })
        }

        #[pallet::call_index(1)]
        #[pallet::weight(10_000)]
        pub fn decrement(origin: OriginFor<T>) -> DispatchResult {
            let who = ensure_signed(origin)?;
            CounterValue::<T>::try_mutate(|val| {
                let new_val = val.checked_sub(1).ok_or(Error::<T>::Underflow)?;
                *val = new_val;
                Self::deposit_event(Event::CounterDecremented { new_value: new_val, who });
                Ok(())
            })
        }
    }
}
```

Key differences from older FRAME patterns: uses `#[frame::pallet]` macro (not `#[frame_support::pallet]`), `use frame::prelude::*`, the constant is named `CounterMaxValue`, and errors are `Overflow`/`Underflow`/`CounterMaxValueExceeded`. The `extern crate alloc` is required because the pallet uses `no_std` and needs `Vec` for genesis.

Open runtime/src/configs/mod.rs. Add the Config implementation for the custom pallet at the end of the file:

```rust
impl pallet_custom::Config for Runtime {
    type RuntimeEvent = RuntimeEvent;
    type CounterMaxValue = ConstU32<100>;
}
```

The constant name is CounterMaxValue (matching the pallet's Config trait). ConstU32<100> sets the upper bound to 100 — adjust as needed. ConstU32 is from frame_support::traits and is already available in the parachain template runtime.

Find the #[frame_support::runtime] macro block in runtime/src/lib.rs and add the Counter pallet:

```rust
#[frame_support::runtime]
mod runtime {
    // ... existing pallets ...

    #[runtime::pallet_index(50)]
    pub type Counter = pallet_custom;
}
```

Choose a pallet_index value not used by any existing pallet. The name Counter is the on-chain pallet identifier used in storage keys and extrinsic prefixes.

Create a file named query.ts with the following content. Replace INSERT_ADDRESS with the SS58-encoded address to query (e.g., an address from the create-polkadot-account skill output):

```typescript
import 'dotenv/config';
import { ApiPromise, WsProvider } from '@polkadot/api';

async function main() {
  const provider = new WsProvider(process.env.WS_ENDPOINT!);
  const api = await ApiPromise.create({ provider });
  const chain = await api.rpc.system.chain();
  const existentialDeposit = api.consts.balances.existentialDeposit;
  console.log(`Connected to: ${chain}`);
  console.log(`Existential deposit: ${existentialDeposit.toHuman()}`);
  const account = await api.query.system.account('INSERT_ADDRESS');
  console.log('Account data:', account.toHuman());
  await api.disconnect();
}
```

main().catch(console.error);

steps.expected_output:
Connected to: Polkadot (or your target chain name)
Existential deposit: 10 mDOT (or equivalent)
Account data: { nonce: ..., data: { free: ..., reserved: ... } }

steps.description:
Create a file named transfer.ts. Only proceed if MNEMONIC is set in .env. Replace INSERT_RECIPIENT with the destination SS58 address and INSERT_AMOUNT with the transfer amount in planck units (e.g., 1000000000000 = 1 DOT with 10 decimals, or 1000000000000000000 = 1 PAS with 18 decimals):

```typescript
import 'dotenv/config';
import { ApiPromise, WsProvider, Keyring } from '@polkadot/api';

async function main() {
  const provider = new WsProvider(process.env.WS_ENDPOINT!);
  const api = await ApiPromise.create({ provider });
  const keyring = new Keyring({ type: 'sr25519' });
  const sender = keyring.addFromUri(process.env.MNEMONIC!);
  console.log(`Sending from: ${sender.address}`);
  const txHash = await api.tx.balances
    .transferKeepAlive('INSERT_RECIPIENT', INSERT_AMOUNT)
    .signAndSend(sender);
  console.log(`Transaction hash: ${txHash}`);
  await api.disconnect();
}
```

main().catch(console.error);

Then run: npx tsx transfer.ts

Create a new file at src/wagmi.ts (or wagmi.ts in the project root if using the src/ layout). Paste the following content exactly:

```typescript
import { createConfig, http } from 'wagmi';
import { defineChain } from 'viem';
import { injected } from 'wagmi/connectors';

export const polkadotHubTestnet = defineChain({
  id: 420420417,
  name: 'Polkadot Hub TestNet',
  nativeCurrency: { name: 'PAS', symbol: 'PAS', decimals: 18 },
  rpcUrls: {
    default: { http: ['https://services.polkadothub-rpc.com/testnet'] },
  },
});

export const config = createConfig({
  chains: [polkadotHubTestnet],
  connectors: [injected()],
  transports: {
    [polkadotHubTestnet.id]: http(),
  },
});
```

This configures Wagmi to use Polkadot Hub TestNet as the only chain with the injected (MetaMask) connector.

Open src/app/layout.tsx (or pages/_app.tsx if using pages router). Add a client-side providers wrapper. Create src/app/providers.tsx with:

```typescript
'use client';
import { WagmiProvider } from 'wagmi';
import { QueryClient, QueryClientProvider } from '@tanstack/react-query';
import { config } from '../wagmi';

const queryClient = new QueryClient();

export function Providers({ children }: { children: React.ReactNode }) {
  return (
    <WagmiProvider config={config}>
      <QueryClientProvider client={queryClient}>
        {children}
